        "richtext_byRzpG": {
          "type": "richtext",
          "settings": {
            "rich_text_content": "<h2>What Is Special About Athletes With Small Wrists?</h2><p>One of the main gender differences between men and women is <a href=\"https://www.cdc.gov/nchs/data/nhsr/nhsr010.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">that the former are proportionately larger</a> across populations. Additionally, <a href=\"https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7502892/\" target=\"_blank\">more men are going to the gym</a> and participating in weightlifting, although the gap has been shrinking in recent years thanks to destigmatization. As such, it can be difficult to find appropriately sized lifting straps for women, as most of the market is tailored towards men.</p><p>Moreover, the study comparing carpal bone size in men and women found that <a href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15680553/\" target=\"_blank\">women had smaller wrists</a> than men on average. However, it points out that people of similar size, regardless of gender, would have similar-sized wrists. In hindsight, this suggests that men of smaller proportions also face difficulties finding lifting straps for small wrists.</p><p>As an authority in the world of weightlifting, with staff ranging from professional coaches to Olympic athletes, we decided to compile this list of the best lifting straps for small wrists. Hopefully, it helps more female weightlifters and more athletes of generally smaller proportions find the right-sized lifting straps.</p><h2>Benefits of Using Lifting Straps for Small Wrists (Why Small Wrists Need Lifting Straps More)</h2><p>Lifting straps wouldn’t have been created if they didn’t have a purpose. Here’s how lifting straps benefit you and why they’re even more important for smaller wrists:</p>",
            "rich_text_image_alt": "",
            "half_width_main_image": false
          }
        },
        "image_JH8tqA": {
          "type": "image",
          "settings": {
            "image": "shopify://shop_images/training-best-lifting-straps-women-best-choice-1024x683.jpg",
            "image_alt": "lifting straps women best choice",
            "half_width_main_image": false
          }
        },
        "richtext_JmGC4V": {
          "type": "richtext",
          "settings": {
            "rich_text_content": "<h3>1. Improving Grip</h3><p>The main purpose of using lifting straps for women and men is to improve grip. Grip strength is a common weak point for athletes of various fitness levels. Unless specifically trained, it grows disproportionately to other muscles, often simply due to muscle size differences (think forearm muscles vs. trapezius, for example).</p><p>When lifting straps are on, they spread some of the weight away from your grip and onto your forearms. That way, you can use forearm strength to lift more weight. If you want to get even more specific, another study showed that lifting straps helped female lifters perform more deadlift reps <a href=\"https://journals.lww.com/nsca-jscr/abstract/2023/10000/the_effect_of_lifting_straps_on_deadlift.2.aspx#:~:text=Results%20indicate%20that%20using%20LS,training%20involving%20the%20deadlift%20exercise.\" target=\"_blank\">by preserving grip strength</a>.</p><p>But this effect isn’t exclusive to weightlifting exercises. A similar effect is also transferable to other pull-based exercises like lateral pulldowns or pull-ups. That way, lifting straps can easily assist with small wrists bodybuilding, calisthenics, and more.</p><h3>Pro Tip:</h3><p><em>\"Avoid using lifting straps for lifts that are easily manageable for you. That way, you naturally develop grip strength and avoid overreliance on gear that might simply be unnecessary.\"</em></p><h3>2. Avoiding Injuries</h3><p>Research suggests that smaller wrist circumference is tied to an <a href=\"https://www.mdpi.com/2077-0383/11/23/7048\" target=\"_blank\">increased risk of fractures</a>, and this trend is more true among women. In addition to this data, female weightlifters report a <a href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21590644/\" target=\"_blank\">higher rate of wrist and hand injuries</a> than male lifters.</p><p>By using lifting traps and reducing the chance of grip failure, we also avoid damage sustained by it, mitigating these long and short-term effects and keeping wrists healthier for longer.</p><h3>3. Mental Edge</h3><p>Studies looking at the effects of lifting straps on grip and performance also found that those who wore them also <a href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33306977/\" target=\"_blank\">had an improved perception of exertion and grip security</a>. In simple terms, their confidence in completing the lift was also higher, further suggesting the potential of using lifting straps for especially tough-to-manage lifts.</p><h2>When Do You Need Wrist Straps?</h2><p>Some people view lifting straps as cheating, especially in competitive environments. It’s not unheard of for them to be banned from lifting competitions due to their effects on grip and strength. That said, there are situations where they become more of a necessity than just a beneficial:</p>",
