        "richtext_nC3qmd": {
          "type": "richtext",
          "settings": {
            "rich_text_content": "<h3>1. Weak Grip</h3><p>Many people find that their grip strength fails first when doing grip-intensive exercises. This is even more true for a small wrists female vs. an average-sized male. Moreover, this happens even more frequently when doing exercises with higher repetition numbers vs. simply 1-rep maxing. If you find this to be the case for you as well, consider adding lifting straps. </p><h3>2. Wrist Issues</h3><p>If you’re dealing with injuries such as fractures or medical conditions like Carpal Tunnel Syndrome (CTS), you may struggle to maintain your grip during exercise. These conditions can cause discomfort and make gripping weights challenging. In such situations, using lifting straps can help alleviate pressure on your hands and wrists, making lifts more manageable.</p><p>Additionally, it's worth noting that female lifters tend to experience wrist injuries more frequently than male lifters, which further emphasizes the importance of wearing weight lifting wrist straps for women.</p><h3>3. Sensitive Skin</h3><p>An often-forgotten benefit of wearing lifting straps to alleviate grip pressure is the reduced tension on your palm skin. By displacing some of the weight from your palms and onto your forearms, you’ll sustain fewer and more manageable skin abrasions. Calluses especially come to mind. Although not set in stone, it’s a safe assumption that female lifters will care about this even more.</p><h3>Pro Tip:</h3><p><em>\"There’s no shame in using assistance gear if your physical well-being is a concern. Lift straps can make a big difference if you have any type of wrist issue.\"</em></p><h2>How to Choose Lifting Straps for Small Wrists (Women & Men)</h2><p>Consider the following factors when buying weight lifting wrist straps for women and men with smaller wrists:</p><h3>1. Strap Type</h3><p>Lasso lifting straps with an adjustable wrist fit are good pretty much across the board. Just narrow the fit down to your wrist and they’ll feel great. Olympic straps can be hit or miss depending on the length of the strap itself, but are generally pretty customizable, too.</p>",
