        "richtext_keUCwn": {
          "type": "richtext",
          "settings": {
            "rich_text_content": "<p>A longer strap can make tying more secure, which is helpful for small wrists. Figure 8 straps are easy to slip into but are typically less tight-fitting, so sizing is crucial. The wrong size can prove unusable for a small wrists female, for example.</p><h3>2. Material</h3><p>Most lifting straps are made out of cotton, as it is a soft material that tends to fit well with all wrist shapes. Cotton straps shouldn’t be particularly abrasive even when under pressure, compared to something like leather. Leather straps are a bit more abrasive and can dig into the skin under high pressure, so it’s best to use them for single-repetition lifts.</p><h3>3. Exercise Type</h3><p>When it comes to multiple-repetition exercises, such as pulldowns or rows, consider using longer straps that loop around the handle or barbell, as they’re less likely to come. If you want something quick and easy to use for shorter weightlifting reps, figure 8 straps are a great choice. </p><h3>4. Durability</h3><p>Quality material and stitching play a big part in the durability of lifting straps. Look for reinforced stitching at key pressure points. Cotton is perfect for blending comfort and durability, tough leather straps are a bit more durable, but also more expensive.</p>",
