          "type": "richtext",
          "settings": {
            "rich_text_content": "<h3>5. Value For Money</h3><p>Conventional thinking usually goes that a bigger price equals better quality, but this isn’t always the case. When buying straps from a big brand, you’re often paying disproportionately for name value. In the case of weightlifting, specialized brands like Warm Body Cold Mind and Rogue can offer better price points.</p><h2>FAQ</h2><h3>What Size Wrist Straps Are Best for Small Wrists?</h3><p>Smaller wrists tend to be <a href=\"https://medlineplus.gov/ency/imagepages/17182.htm\" target=\"_blank\">around 5.5 inches</a> (U.S. and Europe). Most wrist straps are a one-size-fits-all design. Go for lasso straps if you want to get an exact fit. Otherwise, look for smaller-sized straps built for under &lt;7 inches circumference.</p><h3>What Are the Easiest Lifting Straps to Use?</h3><p>When it comes to ease of use, figure 8 lifting straps arguably reign supreme. They can be slid on and off in a second and even less with some experience.</p>",
